<p>A brag document is a simple, living record of the work you have done, the things you have shipped, the problems you have solved, and the impact you have had. Despite the slightly uncomfortable name, the point is not to be arrogant. It is to create a clear, useful source of truth about what you have actually accomplished, especially in contexts where other people may not know the full scope of your work.</p>

<p>The idea is especially valuable because good work is often invisible, scattered across projects, or forgotten by the time someone needs to describe it. A brag document gives you and others a place to quickly understand your strengths, your progress, and your credibility. It can help with resumes, introductions, promotions, speaking opportunities, performance reviews, and any moment where someone needs to explain why you are worth paying attention to.</p>

<p>It also makes self-promotion feel less awkward. Instead of trying to hype yourself up on the spot, you are simply documenting facts as they happen. Over time, the document becomes a practical confidence tool: a reminder of what you have built, what you have learned, and where your work has mattered.</p>